This paper is primarily focused on the inductive bias of convolutional networks in the context of computer vision tasks, which suggests that it is likely to belong to the Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition (cs.CV) sub-category. The paper also involves theoretical analysis and empirical validation of convolutional networks, which suggests that it may also belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) and Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE) sub-categories. The paper discusses the ability of convolutional networks to model correlations among regions of their input, which suggests that it may also belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. Finally, the paper involves analyzing the pooling geometry of convolutional networks, which suggests that it may also belong to the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-category.
